    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_843965323" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/843965323" />
    <a title="Christopher Trader" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1816075-christopher-trader"><img alt="Christopher Trader" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1230402414p2/1816075.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/843965323?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher Trader" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher Trader" href="/user/show/1816075-christopher-trader">Christopher Trader</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">EVERYONE</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer843965323" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16241827940950696119">I must admit, right from the start, that this will be a very poor review. It will be a poor review because such a work of wonder and artistry could never be properly praised with mere words alone. I fear I lack the talent to even come near doing justice to the education this book has given me. To the depth of philosophy and emotion drawn forth by Wright&apos;s writing. <br/><br/>I want to start by sharing why I chose to read this work. Many years ago I purchased a copy of Wright&apos;s work, Native Son. I don&apos;t rem</span>
  <span id="freeText16241827940950696119" style="display:none">I must admit, right from the start, that this will be a very poor review. It will be a poor review because such a work of wonder and artistry could never be properly praised with mere words alone. I fear I lack the talent to even come near doing justice to the education this book has given me. To the depth of philosophy and emotion drawn forth by Wright's writing. <br /><br />I want to start by sharing why I chose to read this work. Many years ago I purchased a copy of Wright's work, Native Son. I don't remember what led me to it, but nevertheless I read it and fell madly in love with Wright's talent as a story-crafter and writer. I was floored both with his talent and with the content of the story, but this is not a review of Native Son, so I will digress. <br /><br />After reading Native Son and being absolutely amazed with Wright's talents, I wanted to read more by him, including this book, Black Boy, his Autobiography. I found it to be one of the most grammatically soothing books I have ever read, though it was a tough read emotionally at times. Wright goes into detail in this book about crafting perfect sentences, about his desire as a writer to formulate his words in a detailed but pleasing manner. I believe he really understated this in it's description, but his writing itself shows the truth of it.<br /><br />Every sentence, paragraph, and even word is carefully chosen by Wright as he composes. This is not Literature, but perfected prose. When you read Wright you don't hit dry patches that make you long for the next section of the work. You don't feel that you are performing a task in reading his works, instead you feel as though you are reading the finest poetry from the comfort of a blanket in the middle of the most beautiful park you've ever seen, on the most perfect summer day you could ever imagine. <br /><br />Aside from the writing itself, the content of this book is stunning in it's detail and magnitude. Wright manages not just to describe situations in his life to you, but to place you into those situations, to give you a glimpse of feeling what it is that he felt. I find this especially important for the White reader in America. Many white's feel as though we are sensitive to African American issues and understand their culture, but I tell you here that you will admit to yourself after reading this book that you truly had not one half of the understanding that you thought you did. <br /><br />The book is composed of two major sections, the first being Wright's upbringing in the South, and the latter half detailing his young adult life in the North (Chicago). We learn, deeply, the struggles of growing up in the South as an African American. The pure degradation, fear, hunger, and angst of it all. Wright also goes into much detail of the suffering he withstood from being raised in a deeply religious home, and the poison and division this can create amongst a family. <br /><br />Once in the North we learn how differently interactions are between White and Black vs. how they are in the South, but are also shown the inner fear and paranoia that can make life just as dreadful as it is in the South. <br /><br />***SMALL SPOILERS BELOW***<br /><br />The overall content of the book details Wright's learning to read at a young age, his hunger and desire to use this ability, and its eventually leading to his desire to write. The other major events cover Wright's dealings with the Communist Party of the U.S. and their eventual betrayal of him. <br /><br />For Leftist readers there is a lot of eye-opening here. We are shown the inner-workings of a leftist political party, for good or bad. It was most interesting to me because I had no idea Wright was involved with the CPUSA, and being a staunch Leftist myself it was almost serendipitous to find this being covered in a book that I had not sought out for this reason. Without going into too much detail, I just want to note that I not only suggest this as reading for ALL white's in America, but especially for any and every person with a Leftist bent. <br /><br />Overall my head is spinning after reading this book. There is so much to think about and process. I'll probably read the book again just to take notes and give the book the deep analysis that it truly deserves. Wright is one of the smartest and most eloquent writers I have ever come across, and this book is a prime example of this. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16241827940950696119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


