<span id="freeTextContainer947373413054758529">Native Son was assigned in one of my university courses, and I remember it was an electrifying experience for me. I remember doing coursework at a local Starbucks and feeling like I could not put down the book. Of course, we never discussed it fully during our course and I ended up buying <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/228630.Black_Boy' title='Black Boy by Richard Wright' rel='nofollow noopener'>Black Boy</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54761.Uncle_Tom_s_Children' title='Uncle Tom&apos;s Children by Richard Wright' rel='nofollow noopener'>Uncle Tom&apos;s Children</a>. Recently, I had to organize my book collection at my family home and came across the Harper Perennial Centennial edition of Black Boy.<br/><br/>I read it these past two weeks and the s</span>
  <span id="freeText947373413054758529" style="display:none">Native Son was assigned in one of my university courses, and I remember it was an electrifying experience for me. I remember doing coursework at a local Starbucks and feeling like I could not put down the book. Of course, we never discussed it fully during our course and I ended up buying <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/228630.Black_Boy" title="Black Boy by Richard Wright" rel="nofollow noopener">Black Boy</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54761.Uncle_Tom_s_Children" title="Uncle Tom's Children by Richard Wright" rel="nofollow noopener">Uncle Tom's Children</a>. Recently, I had to organize my book collection at my family home and came across the Harper Perennial Centennial edition of Black Boy.<br /><br />I read it these past two weeks and the scenes and the images took a strong hold in my mind that I became very unsettled and had to take breaks from reading it. From the first scene when Richard accidentally sets fire to the house, to his days of being a drunkard to what he did to the poor kitten, it was very hard to read it. Richard's experiences under Jim Crow South is necessary reading for understanding the black experience in America. This is a groundbreaking memoir. So many despicable scenes and horrifying crimes - it all happened less than 100 years ago. It's just insane! <br /><br />Richard shows us a part of life and a group of the disenfranchised and how they live - this is one of the higher purposes of good writing. Richard provides insights into the writing process when he expresses how he learned more about good writing by reading, and his frustrations at making shoddy writing that didn't reflect his ambitions, or when he expresses his desire to write because it was his way of existing, surviving in the world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="947373413054758529" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
